<section xml:id="sec-solving-first-order-linear" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Solving First-Order Linear ODEs</title>

  <p>We will rely heavily on the product rule, so below is a quick refresher! It also goes into how we specifically use it in this page.
  </p>
   <p>Before diving in, you may want to review the product rule:</p>

<solution xml:id="prereq-product-rule">
  <title>Prerequisite: The Product Rule</title>
  <p>
    If <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are both functions of <m>x</m>, then
    <me>(f \cdot g)' = f'g + fg'.</me>
    For example, with <m>f(x) = x^2</m> and <m>g(x) = e^x</m>:
    <me>(x^2 e^x)' = 2x e^x + x^2 e^x.</me>
    Now consider <m>f(x) = e^{2x}</m> and <m>g(x) = y(x)</m>, where <m>y</m> is a function of <m>x</m>:
    <me>\left(e^{2x} \cdot y\right)' = 2e^{2x} y + e^{2x} y'.</me>
  </p>
</solution>
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       MOTIVATING INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <p>
    Okay so now we know how to recognize when an equation is a first-order linear ODE, let's dig into
    how to actually solve these things! We'll work through
    <me>y' + 2y = x</me>
    as our guiding example. The steps may seem a bit random at first, but hopefully by the end of this page you'll
    see why we did each step. The key idea is to find an <term>integrating factor</term>, which is
    a function we multiply both sides by that lets us rewrite the left-hand side
    as the derivative of a product. Once we do that, we can simply integrate both sides
    and solve for <m>y</m>.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       MOTIVATING EXPLORATION
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <exploration xml:id="exp-integrating-factor-intro">
    <title>Solving <m>y' + 2y = x</m></title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        It turns out the integrating factor for this equation is <m>e^{2x}</m>.
        We will see exactly why this is the right choice shortly. For now, let's
        multiply both sides by <m>e^{2x}</m> and see what happens.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>y' + 2y \amp= x</mrow>
        <mrow>e^{2x}(y' + 2y) \amp= e^{2x} \cdot x</mrow>
        <mrow>e^{2x}y' + 2e^{2x}y \amp= xe^{2x}</mrow>
      </md>
    </introduction>

    <task xml:id="task-recognize-product-rule">
      <title>Reversing the Product Rule</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Look closely at the left-hand side: <m>e^{2x}y' + 2e^{2x}y</m>.
          Which of the following is this equal to? You might need to perform the product rule in some of the choices below!
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p><m>\left(e^{2x} y\right)'</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Yes! By the product rule, <m>\left(e^{2x} y\right)' = e^{2x}y' + 2e^{2x}y</m>,
              which is exactly the left-hand side. We have reversed the product rule,
              and can now write our equation as
              <me>\left(e^{2x} y\right)' = xe^{2x}.</me>
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\left(e^{2x}\right)' \cdot y'</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Not quite. <m>\left(e^{2x}\right)' = 2e^{2x}</m>, so this gives <m>2e^{2x}y'</m>,
              which does not match.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>e^{2x}(y' + y)</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Close, but distributing gives <m>e^{2x}y' + e^{2x}y</m>.
              The coefficient on <m>y</m> needs to be <m>2e^{2x}</m>, not <m>e^{2x}</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\left(e^{2x} + y\right)'</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              No -- this is the derivative of a sum, not a product.
              We need the product rule here.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>

    <task xml:id="task-recognize-integrate">
      <title>What is the Next Step?</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We now have
          <me>\left(e^{2x} y\right)' = xe^{2x}.</me>
          The left-hand side is a derivative. What should we do next to solve for <m>y</m>?
        </p>
        <p>
          <alert>Make sure to read the solution feedback by clicking the right answer to see how to finish solving for y.</alert>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>Integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Exactly. Integrating both sides gives
              <me>e^{2x} y = \int xe^{2x}\,dx,</me>
              and dividing by <m>e^{2x}</m> yields
              <me>y = \frac{\int xe^{2x}\,dx}{e^{2x}}.</me>
              The integral on the right requires integration by parts -- we will return to
              computing it fully later in this section.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Differentiating would make things more complicated.
              Since the left-hand side is already a derivative, we want to undo it by integrating.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>Divide both sides by <m>e^{2x}</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Dividing is part of the last step, but we are not quite there yet.
              The left-hand side is <m>(e^{2x} y)'</m>, not <m>e^{2x} y</m>.
              We need to integrate first, then divide.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>Multiply both sides by <m>e^{-2x}</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Multiplying by <m>e^{-2x}</m> is equivalent to dividing by <m>e^{2x}</m>,
              which comes after integrating, not before.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>

    <conclusion>
      <p>
        Let's take stock of what just happened, because the structure here is the key to
        solving <em>any</em> first-order linear ODE.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Step 1.</alert> We multiplied both sides by the integrating factor <m>e^{2x}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Step 2.</alert> This allowed us to recognize the left-hand side as
        <m>\left(e^{2x} y\right)'</m> by reversing the product rule.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Step 3.</alert> With the left-hand side written as a single derivative,
        there is no <m>y'</m> term to deal with separately. We simply integrate both sides
        and solve for <m>y</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The whole game is choosing the integrating factor correctly so that Step 2 works.
        Let's see how to do that in general.
      </p>
    </conclusion>
  </exploration>

  <p>
    So do we need to guess and check for an integrating factor every time? Not at all!
    It turns out that for any first-order linear ODE
    <me>\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x),</me>
    the integrating factor is always
    <me>\rho(x) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}.</me>
    This is precisely what is needed to rewrite the left-hand side in the form
    <m>\left(y \cdot \rho(x)\right)'</m>, which is what allows us to integrate both sides
    and solve for <m>y</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you feel like it now, you can try working through why this is true by multiplying
    <m>\rho(x)</m> on both sides of <m>\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)</m> yourself. You can
    check the justification now, or later after you've had more practice with solving these ODEs!
  </p>

  <solution>
    <title>Justification of the Integrating Factor (optional to read now)</title>
    <p>
      Multiply both sides of <m>\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)</m> by
      <m>\rho(x) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}</m>:
      <me>e^{\int P(x)\,dx}\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)e^{\int P(x)\,dx}y = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}Q(x).</me>
      Now look at the left-hand side. By the product rule and the chain rule:
      <me>\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(y \cdot e^{\int P(x)\,dx}\right) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}y' + P(x)e^{\int P(x)\,dx}y,</me>
      which is exactly the left-hand side. So we can write:
      <me>\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(y \cdot e^{\int P(x)\,dx}\right) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}Q(x).</me>
      From here, integrate both sides and solve for <m>y</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       THEOREM
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <theorem xml:id="thm-first-order-linear-solution">
    <title>Solution of a First-Order Linear ODE</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The general solution of the first-order linear equation
        <me>\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)</me>
        can be found by multiplying both sides by the <term>integrating factor</term>
        <me>\rho(x) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx},</me>
        which allows the equation to be rewritten as
        <me>\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(y \cdot \rho(x)\right) = \rho(x)\,Q(x).</me>
        Integrating both sides and solving for <m>y</m> gives the general solution
        <me>y = \frac{\displaystyle\int \rho(x)\,Q(x)\,dx}{\rho(x)}.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       POST-THEOREM: connect to example (inline prose)
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <p>
    Let's connect this back to our example <m>y' + 2y = x</m>.
    Here <m>P(x) = 2</m> and <m>Q(x) = x</m>, so the integrating factor is
    <me>\rho(x) = e^{\int 2\,dx} = e^{2x},</me>
    which is exactly what we used in the exploration above.
    The general solution takes the form
    <me>y = \frac{\int xe^{2x}\,dx}{e^{2x}} = \frac{\frac{x}{2}e^{2x} - \frac{1}{4}e^{2x} + C}{e^{2x}}.</me>
    where we evaluated <m>\int xe^{2x}\,dx</m> using integration by parts.
  </p>
  <p>
    The theorem tells us this approach works for <em>any</em> first-order linear ODE, not just this one.
    The only thing that can get in our way now is if the integrals that appear are difficult to evaluate!
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
